page.title: 04UPLAND-HOLKER MOSS
page.content: The land in the east of the area is part of the highland of the{Cartmel {Peninsula}reaching heights of 150 to 200m.The highest point is a small hill of 205m. which overlooks Bigland Tarn. To the west of the highland,there is a continuous slope following a north- south fault scarp. The main rock type is{slate.}The highland landscape undulates with rocky outcrops and marshy hollows.The poor drainage of the area results in marshy areas and small ponds.One of these is called "Bigland Tarn",and is larger than the majority of the other ponds. The land was probably{glaciated}at one time when "plucking"and"abrasion" by ice played a part in forming the landscape leaving exposed,rocky outcrops separated by marshy hollows filled in with deposits.
